Yes â€” if you follow this approach and import your dailyLeadTest.js file into your index.js (or server.js), it will automatically send a lead once a day as long as your server is running.

âœ… What You Need to Do
1. Create the dailyLeadTest.js file






// dailyLeadTest.js
import cron from "node-cron";
import axios from "axios";

const LEAD_API_URL = "https://yourdomain.com/api/lead"; // âœ… Update this

const sendTestLead = async () => {
  try {
    const response = await axios.post(LEAD_API_URL, {
      name: "Test User",
      email: "testuser@example.com",
      phone: "9999999999",
      source: "daily-cron-test",
    });
    console.log("âœ… Lead test sent successfully:", response.data);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("âŒ Lead test failed:", err.response?.data || err.message);
  }
};

// Schedule to run every day at 9:00 AM
cron.schedule("0 9 * * *", () => {
  console.log("ğŸ•˜ Running daily lead test...");
  sendTestLead();
});




2. Import This File in Your index.js (or app.js or server.js)
Add this line near the top of your index.js file:




import './dailyLeadTest.js'; // ğŸ‘ˆ This starts the cron job when server starts




âœ”ï¸ Result
Your Express server starts.

The cron job gets registered.

Every day at 9:00 AM server time, it sends a test lead to your backend route (/api/lead).

Youâ€™ll see success or error logs in your terminal.

ğŸ”” Important Notes
Make sure your server stays running 24/7, e.g., on VPS, Render, Railway, etc.

If you're deploying to something like Render or Vercel (serverless), the cron job wonâ€™t work unless it's a background process.

If you're using PM2, it will work just fine as long as the app is running.
